<br>
Doesn't always kill?<br>
<br>
In other words I only need to get 5600 hp to survive a MB from a wizard with mostly old world plane gear...<br>
<br>
Very comforting I only need aegeo, around 100 more stamina, 12 aa to burn on combat dur and full VT gear so I can get 125 hp per slot yay.<br>
<br>
God help me if he/she crits though.<br>
<br>
It is unbalanced because a MB wiz with full manna CAN kill 99% of players buffed or unbuffed by pushing a hotkey for gods sake.<br>
<br>
Real pvp design provides skill sets and classes that are BALANCED ENOUGH not perfectly balanced.  In other words there is a food chain but everyone has a chance.<br>
<br>
Good pvp is diverse and situationally unbalanced.  In other words  different situations and circumstances provide different advantages and disadvantages for different classes.  Skilled play should be required both to make use of advantages and to mitigate disadvantages.  The sum of these advantages and disadvantages should be such that pvp is challenging for all classes but neither impossible nor ridiculously easy no matter the match up.  <br>
<br>
I propose that MB makes pvp with every other class a joke when its in use.<br>
<br>
In general the more powerful the skill the more it should be balanced by limitiations as to which situations it can be used in, disadvantages, skill required to execute properly, increasingly effective countermeasures available to oponents.<br>
<br>
I propose that MBs current time limitiation is a joke, that it is usable in all situations, that no skill is required to use it, that no effective countermeasures exist for most classes, and that the disadvantage of using all manna is insignifigant when the battle is allready won and the loot taken.  Especially when the wiz can simply insta gate with a bit more aa.<br>
<br>
In general all pvp strategies should be to a degree situational and that countermeasures for any strategy should always exist.  The result of this kind of design is an interesting and changable pvp environment as its benificial for both parties to use a variety of strategies and counter strategies.<br>
<br>
When one strategy is overwelmingly powerful or useful above all others pvp becomes a boring and simple minded excercise in which both parties pick the &quot;obvious&quot; strategy and the outcome is just a math problem based on gear lvl class.<br>
<br>
<br>
Mannaburn fits that description.<br>
<br>
When one pvp strategy is overwelmingly powerful and lacks counters pvp for the user becomes ridiculously easy, lacking in challenge, and uninteresting, and there is little or no respect on the part of the community for the class as a result.<br>
<br>
For the oponent of such an overpowered char pvp is frustrating and lame because there is no excitement when the outcome is not only allready certain but beyond your ability ot effect and control.<br>
<br>
Again Mannaburn fits that description. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/usollaiel.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sollaiel</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(7/29/02 7:56:55 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=82.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re</span><hr size=1> Well, I don't see any sense in nerfing Spell output by 20-30% if resists aren't as well.. <br>
